  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency and naturalness at the level of individual mutation operators and by keeping the target question fixed (i.e., semantically critical content is not changed). Mutators (e.g., Rephrase, Shorten) explicitly instruct the LLM to preserve overall meaning, and the mutation is performed by an LLM to produce coherent, natural text. However, the design does not provide an explicit mechanism to control cumulative distortion relative to the original seed across many mutation iterations (no similarity-to-original constraint or global plausibility tracker). The authors mitigate over-exploitation of deep mutation chains via a reward-depth penalty (α), but this is an indirect mitigation rather than an explicit preservation of original-seed semantics across iterations. These properties match the metric’s “Medium” level: semantic consistency and naturalness are enforced where applicable between successive mutation steps, but the fuzzer does not account for accumulated drift over repeated mutations.",
